yeah no gotta tear away some of the nostalgic gauze offices were reserved for management and plebes got cubicles company cars were for sales and executives

i remember where as a woman it was dresses and skirts only except fridays you could wear slacks stockingspanty hose were mandatory no open toed shoes were allowed cubicles were the norm same with actually using a typewriter i also remember being told that i was pretty enough i should find a husband for insurance i had been sexually harassed at multiple companies and no one cared i was even fired multiple times for not cooperating and allowing my boss to do whatever man i love working from home

most of this isnt remotely true outside of high level executives most office staff have work in cubicles for 50 years no one got cars unless you were a traveling sales rep virtually everyone talked directly into their receiver which was corded to their desk you still get parking lots and occasional dinners in most corporate jobs less in major cities where public transportation is still an option

for those working for the federal government the cafeterias in the building of each agency sold pretty good food for cheap given that we technically only have 30 min for lunch it was imperative that food was sold onsite and one perk was that it was significantly cheaper than what was sold outside in restaurants no longer particularly after the pandemic hellhole indeed!
i've been working full time since 2002 never had a company car and never had my own office i don't think these things were common in the 80s or 90s either unless you were executive staff
